------=_NextPart_000_0047_01BD8FDE.B32CA0C0
	charset="iso-8859-1"

CJR Jarvis once wrote:

>can anyone give me idea how feasable it is to run an anim off
>disk as the backdrop to a game?


or something like that.
The easiest way to do this is to save every frame of your anim out =
seperately from the paint programme as an IFF. However, IFF is far too =
slow to spool straight from CD, as you probably know. The answer is to =
get hold of a programme called IFFTrasher (or similar) off the Aminet =
(GFX/convert) and use this to convert ALL the frames to RAW data. This =
is the exact way in which the bitplanes are stored in the Amiga memory. =
This means that you can load these RAW images straight into memory =
without any time required for decoding. RAW images are just that, =
though. They contain no palette data, nor anything about the width, =
height or bitplanes of an image. You will need to save the palette =
yourself from DPaint and load this into Blitz (or even have a different =
palette for every frame). Double buffering is absolutely essential here, =
otherwise the screen is totally corrupted. It DOES run at 50fps though! =
If file sizes are getting a bit big, it is still just about possible on =
an '040 and above to load in RAW images compressed with =
Stonecracker/Crunchmania (STC is faster). However, this is pushing =
things a bit. Hope that sorts ya! As for collision detection...you're on =
your own! No, really, you could have a 2/4-colour bitmap loaded in as =
well for detecting platforms. Haven't tried this, though.

Nick / Scillo

