 And about 'new' amiga games. If you want games on your machine, then you'll
have to put up with needing fast hardware. I used to program games back
in the day's off the first a500 with 1/2meg chip and 1 floppy. You could
do some great stuff, and still can....but today things have changed. When
pc's got fast and fancy graphics cards, the amiga was in trouble. I can't
even draw some lines on my machine in the same time as my 150 pentium
draws an entire 3d display with everything. The problem is that things
have got faster...like memory and processors. The amiga's chip speed
is very slow. The most anyone has of it is 2mb, unless your using an
emulator. And even that's not all available to you. And you can use
256 colours, but that slows the machine down, and you can't really do
anything fast unless you use lores. The problem is that games player's
have come to see better resolutions, better sound. I agree that making
a game 3d doesn't make it any better generally, but you try telling that
to everyone else. I still have my c64...and I see how far that could be
pushed...but there's a limit....and we've reached that on the amiga. All
the tricks have been learnt, and most of them you can't use anymore as
everything needs to be fairly os compliant. And they were pushing that
to the limit before....and were still using the exact same hardware. It's
not sloppy programming....it's just that most of the tricks are impossible
these days...and for the things most ppl are trying to do, wouldn't work.

