I think he was wanting a colour fade. But regarding dissolves, if you
want an ordered dissolve you can simple have an `add' value. You'd
treat all the pixels in the bitmap as offsets. Line 0 would be 0..319
and line 1 would be 320..639, etc... You start with a given pixel, any
one of them. You do the pixel copy. Then you add the `add' value to
the pixel number. If the add value exceeds the last pixel in the
screen, you subtract the total number of pixels from the pixel number,
to wrap around to the top again. This wrapping is important. You have
to select odd numers for your add value AFAIR, and you can experiment
with different numbers. Some wont work, some will. But basically if
you choose a number like, say, 6743, it will likely dissole in every
pixel in the screen. It will have a certain appearance. You will get a
different appearance with different values.

Furthermore, if you have a bitplane free, use it as a `mask in or out'
bitplane. Make the lower half of the palette black and the upper half
the colours you want. Do the ordered dissolve on the bitplane to
dissolve up or down a bitmap from/to black or another colour. You can
also do small chunks, like say divide the height into 8 or 10 or 20
even. Do a dissolve only with that height (like 16 lines), and use a
copy routine to repeat the pattern down the screen.

Anyway...

