what to do.

You can't guarantee 25fps in your game unless you use some very good, fast
optimised code.

In throey your game should run at 50fps, that's the fastest the Amiga can go I
think. Right, if you just do a main loop and note the fps it'll be 50fps,
cause you're not doing anything, just looping around.

Now if you start puttin gthings in your loop, in your case for your game,
it'll start going into subroutines before it can finish the loop. Subroutines
like blitting graphics, moving the display, artificial intelligence, that sort
of thing.

    #Reset Timer#

    #While KeyCode#<>117 ; Wait for ESC key to be hit.

     #VWait#
    
     #If Timer#>49
        fps.q=framecount/1.0
        framecount=0
        #Reset Timer#
     #End if # 

     framecount+1
    #Wend#

This will give you 50fps, no greater, cause you're not doing anything in the
loop. Now if we do an example of a game loop :

    #Reset Timer#

    #While KeyCode#<>117 ; Wait for ESC key to be hit.
    
    #VWait#

     #If Timer#>49
        fps.q=framecount/1.0
        framecount=0
        #Reset Timer#
     #End if # 

     #Gosub# check_inputs
     #Gosub# render_background
     #Gosub# ai_routines
     #Gosub# render_objects 
     
     #ShowBitmap# db : db=1-db

     framecount+1
    #Wend#

In the above loop, before the framecount can be added with one, more ticks are
going to happen because you're going into four subroutines, which will of
course take some valuable ticks up. Now when the ticks are equal to 50 the
number of frame counts counted won't be as high as when you're doing nothing,
therefore a lower frame rate will appear. If you've got processor specific
routines they faster your processor will process them, therefore less time to
do the four routines and give you a higher frame rate.

You can't force a program to have 25fps if it's taking less than 25 frames a
second  to do your entire loop.

If you knew all this, I'm sorry but I thought you where in a bit a muddle with
all this 25fps stuff. :)

